{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493211"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:00:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:00:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1254"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1254"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.29,0.2,0.39,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1254"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29601"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46507"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department complaining of left upper abdominal pain. Two days earlier he had been hit in this area whilst playing football. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/80mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 98% breathing room air. He is tender in the left upper quadrant. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home for review the following day","Admit to the ward for further observation","Splenectomy","Splenic artery embolisation","Diagnostic laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the American Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Injury Scale for the spleen, these CT images show a Grade IV splenic injury (\u0026gt;25-75% devascularisation). The arrow points to the large haematoma (Image). Splenic trauma can be managed surgically or non surgically, depending on the severity of injury and clinical status of the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll splenic trauma Grade IV and V are classed as high grade injuries, with haemodynamically stable patients in these grades referred for \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic artery embolisation (SAE)\u003C/strong\u003E. Thus, as this patient has a normal blood pressure and pulse rate and is otherwise well, SAE is the most appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients who are haemodynamically unstable, surgical management is indicated \u003Cstrong\u003E(splenectomy).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ediagnostic laparoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated as the CT imaging and clinical examination findings provide adequate information to guide appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDue to the high grade of the injury and potential for the patient to become haemodynamically unstable, \u003Cstrong\u003Efurther observation \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Edischarge home for review tomorrow \u003C/strong\u003Eare inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Management of splenic trauma depends on the severity of injury shown on CT and haemodynamic stability of the patient."],"references":["Habash M, Ceballos D, Gunn AJ. Splenic Artery Embolization for Patients with High-Grade Splenic Trauma: Indications, Techniques, and Clinical Outcomes. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2021;38(1):105-112. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33883807/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29601"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1254"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14302"},{"type":"media","id":"14303"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20627"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14302"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b228fb99-8822-4b74-8246-e7b91f63d4bf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b228fb99-8822-4b74-8246-e7b91f63d4bf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":580}},{"type":"media","id":"14303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14303"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e566d286-1492-4038-ac5e-958134027685.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e566d286-1492-4038-ac5e-958134027685.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":568}},{"type":"media","id":"20627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20627"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xBAnxdByMhqNTGzJEplBrulefI8qaf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xBAnxdByMhqNTGzJEplBrulefI8qaf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":568}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29601"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-27T15:50:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T08:16:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44723"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/